The paper proposes a video summarization framework that uses deep convolutional neural networks and restricted Boltzmann machines to generate multimodal representations of video content. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) and multimedia (cs.MM) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper uses a co-regularization scheme to discover meaningful subject-scene associations, which suggests that it may also belong to the information retrieval (cs.IR) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Finally, the paper evaluates its proposed method using a user study, which suggests that it may also belong to the natural language processing (cs.CL) sub-category.
